\abstract{
This report introduces "The Cognitive Development Framework for AI Proficiency," which maps the evolution of AI competency in the accounting profession to Jean Piaget’s four stages of cognitive development. The central premise is that AI adoption progresses through structured stages, where users of AI systems move from basic Awareness of AI applications to the Orchestration of Agent Architecture, thereby ensuring a structured path toward mastery rather than a disjointed adoption of disparate tools. The framework details four phases: the Sensory-Motor Stage (basic chat interactions), the Pre-operational Stage (individual tool use for isolated tasks), the Concrete Operational Stage (manual comparison of multiple model outputs), and the final Formal Operational Stage, where the user architects autonomous agent systems capable of complex function calling and long tasks. Progress is measured by number of tokens generated, and the methods they use to interface with the technology (e.g. chat interface or API calls).
}

