\section{Preface}
Sam Altman - in a video announcing a joint venture called io between OpenAI and Jonny Ive's company LoveFrom - described the fragmented way that users interact with platforms like ChatGPT. I believe that the fragmented series of steps followed to interact with this incredible technology is a sign that we are still early in the development of Artificial Intelligence (AI). And as such, new interfaces and even entirely new AI algorithms will need to be created to deliver on the promises this technology offers. The purpose of this paper and the framework contained in it is to articulate the development of Large Language Models (LLMs) thus far, and define the competency steps for using AI applications, allowing CPA Candidates and licensed CPAs to assess their skill progression. My hope is that this will serve as a framework for others as well.

\section{Introduction}
\firstword{T}{he} % Capital letter in first word 
progression of LLM applications to agentic systems can be analogized to a baby learning to use its muscles, as described by Dr. Maxwell Maltz in the book Psychocybernetics. In the book, he states:

\textbf{\textit{"In a baby, just learning to use its muscles, the correction of the hand in reaching for a rattle is very obvious. The baby has little 'stored information' to draw upon. Its hand zigzags back and forth as it reaches.
It is characteristic of all learning that as learning takes place, correction becomes more and more refined. We see this in a person just learning to drive a car, who 'over-corrects' and zigzags back and forth across the street.
Once, however, a correct or 'successful response' has been accomplished—it is 'remembered' for future use. It has 'learned' how to respond successfully. It 'remembers' its successes, forgets its failures, and repeats the successful action without any further conscious 'thought'—or as a habit."}}

In other words, just as a baby's hand "zigzags back and forth" when reaching for a rattle due to a lack of "stored information," LLMs zigzag across digital workspaces until such time that the tooling is developed to guide them to successful tasks (e.g. making money on the internet). Users of nascent AI applications experience this kind of zigzagging as well. Users follow a fragmented series of steps to get the most out of LLMs, on their way to becoming proficient in the using Software Development Kits (SDKs). Learning - both by the models themselves and the users of these models - is characterized by this initial over-correction, and the zigzag pattern becomes a straight line over time. A "successful response" is remembered and repeated as a habit, in humans, whereas LLMs tend not to have this stored unless the environment, files, and prompts are configured in such a way that they are reminded each time they are instantiated. This "zigzagging" in AI usage, can be found in not only how individuals use this technology, but in how the industry in general uses it.

For example, swaths of individual and business users have migrated from OpenAI to Anthropic. Moreover, even users who have much more mature tooling, will switch between models depending on the use case. They tend to be aware of the pros and cons of specific models.

\section{Theoretical Background: Piaget's Theory of Cognitive Development}

\subsection{Jean Piaget}

Jean Piaget (1896–1980), widely considered the father of modern child psychology, proposed that children move through four distinct stages of mental development as they interact with the world. 

The four stages of Piaget's Theory of Cognitive Development are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Sensorimotor (Birth–2 years): Learning through senses and motor actions; milestone is object permanence.
    \item Preoperational (2–7 years): Symbolic thought (language, pretend play) emerges, but thinking is egocentric and lacks conservation.
    \item Concrete Operational (7–11 years): Logic begins; children can perform mental operations on physical objects and understand conservation. 
    \item Formal Operational (12+ years): Abstract and theoretical reasoning develops, allowing for hypothetical scenarios and systematic problem-solving.
\end{enumerate}

Before Piaget, the prevailing view was that children were simply "miniature adults" who knew less. Piaget proved that children actually process information and perceive reality in entirely different ways than adults do. His key contributions were:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Constructivism
    \item Genetic Epistemology
    \item The Clinical Method
\end{enumerate}

Through my use of LLMs, I noticed that these four cognitive stages provide a precise model for the evolution of both agentic AI systems and the proficiency of individual users. Also, it sets the stage for the next epoch of Artificial Intelligence.

In constructivism, Piaget argued that children are not passive sponges; they are "little scientists" who actively build (construct) their own understanding of the world through experimentation. How this relates to AI is that generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are believed to construct a model of the world that is captured in the weights of their neurons. 

In genetic epistemology, the name for his field of study, Piaget was all about studying genes. But he wasn't interested in genes in a biological sense, rather, the genesis (origin) of knowledge and how the ability to think evolves over time. How this relates to LLMs is that by understanding the algorithm and identifying the benchmarks along which models make progress, you can identify whether or not models are getting better at doing things that humans can do.

Regarding The Clinical Method, unlike researchers who used standardized tests, Piaget interviewed children and observed their mistakes. He realized that the types of mistakes children made were consistent across age groups, which led him to his famous four stages of development. And this relates to LLMs because if you use AI for enough use cases you can start to see that pattern of  mistakes AI makes - across various developers of AI models are similar. 

\section{The Framework}

\subsection{Sensory-Motor Stage: The Awareness Layer}
\textbf{User Proficiency:} At this stage, the professional is merely interacting with the ``chat interface''. They understand that a prompt leads to a response but do not yet grasp the underlying logic. This is characterized by the ``novelty factor'' where utility is not yet integrated into core workflows. \\
\textbf{Model Development:} The LLM operates as a probabilistic text completer. It lacks long-term coherence and relies on the user to provide the entire context for every interaction, mimicking a child's reliance on immediate sensory input. \\
\textbf{Metric:} Basic chat interactions and awareness of public models like ChatGPT and Claude.

\subsection{Pre-operational Stage: Individual Tool Use}
\textbf{User Proficiency:} The professional begins to use AI for symbolic representation, such as drafting emails or summarizing memos. Reasoning is still one-dimensional, and the user remains ``keyboard-heavy,'' manually moving data to and from the chat. \\
\textbf{Model Development:} The model achieves basic instruction-following and maintains a better "mental" model of the prompt's intent. However, it still lacks systematic logic and often ``zigzags'' or hallucinates when faced with complex multi-step reasoning. \\
\textbf{Metric:} Use of consumer-grade applications for isolated tasks; identifying specific use cases (e.g., ``I could use ChatGPT for X!'').

\subsection{Concrete Operational Stage: Rudimentary Workflow Use}
\textbf{User Proficiency:} This is the ``Logic'' phase. The professional understands that AI can follow a sequence of operations along predefined paths. Users begin to judge model outputs manually, often running the same query through multiple models to find consensus. \\
\textbf{Model Development:} Models at this stage exhibit improved ``conservation'' of logic over longer context windows. They can follow rigid "Chain of Thought" paths and interact with structured data, though they still require human "manual comparison" to ensure accuracy. \\
\textbf{Metric:} Parallelization and voting; the shift toward building rudimentary agents using a ``Judge'' agent for consensus.

\subsection{Formal Operational Stage: Agent Architecture}
\textbf{User Proficiency:} The final stage involves abstract reasoning about the system itself. The CPA no longer ``uses'' AI; they ``architect'' it. They use agent harnesses (e.g. Claude Cowork) and have a deep understanding of how all of the pieces fit together. They do not just prompt the LLM within the harness (because that would be indicative of the first stage). Proficiency markers are things such as: do they know about Agent SDKs, do they know what an SDK is, can they build a working agent and develop autonomous systems to carry out some task? Do they account for security concerns and properly address them? \\
\textbf{Model Development:} The AI evolves into an agentic system capable of ``Complex Function Calling'' and long-running tasks. The model can reason about its own errors and self-correct, moving from a zigzagging pattern to a straight line of task execution. \\
\textbf{Outcome:} Creation of autonomous systems that follow commonly known agentic patterns and handle complex, multi-layered problem solving.

